

METROPOLIS, n. A stronghold of provincialism.	
LAWYER, n. One skilled in circumvention of the law.	
KILT, n. A costume sometimes worn by Scotchmen in America and Americans in Scotland.	
JOCKEY, n. A person whose business it is to ride and throw races.	
INCENSE, n. In religious affairs, an argument addressed to the nose.	
HAPPINESS, n. An agreeable sensation arising from contemplating the misery of another.	
GULL, v.t. To tell the sovereign people that if elected you will not steal.	
FORGIVENESS, n. A stratagem to throw an offender off his guard and catch him red-handed in his next offense.	
EDUCATION, n. That which discloses to the wise and disguises from the foolish their lack of understanding.	
DEPRAVED, pp. The moral condition of a gentleman who holds the opposite opinion	
CATECHISM, n. A form of theological riddles in which universal and eternal doubts are resolved by local and fugitive answers.	
AMNESTY, n. The state's magnanimity to those offenders whom it would be too expensive to punish.	
BACCHUS, n. A convenient deity invented by the ancients as an excuse for getting drunk.	
"It may be better to live under robber barons than under omnipotent moral busybodies." - C.S. Lewis	
"Conspiracy theories are how idiots get to feel like intellectuals" - David Baddiel	
"As a rule we disbelieve all the facts and theories for which we have no use." - William James	
"Few things are harder to put up with than the annoyance of a good example." - Mark Twain
"The enemy is anybody who's going to get you killed, no matter which side he's on." - Joseph Heller	
"Calamities are of two kinds: misfortunes to ourselves, and good fortune to others." - Ambrose Bierce
